ce:section.ce:para:
From above ECL investigation results, it can be proposed that appropriate HNO3 etching treatment can change SWCNTs into porous and tubular carbon nanostructures, the walls of which consist of various sizes of mono-layered SP2 structures (Figs. 9
                         and S5), i.e. small-sized GQDs (I), medium-sized GQDs (II), large sized-GQDs (III) and graphene nanoribbons (IV). On the wall of t-GQD-NAs, the various GQDs and graphene nanoribbons should connect with each other by certain SP3 carbon atoms (e.g. CO, CH(OH), or C(OH)2
                        ), and these non-conjugated connections makes the isolated GQDs act like free GQDs. Those GQDs connecting with each other by conjugated SP2 carbon atoms (e.g. one or several fused hexagonal carbon rings) can be regarded as bigger-sized GQDs (like structure III) or even graphene nanoribbons. Due to size effect [60], t-GQD-NAs containing GQDs with various sizes may have different color ECL emissions, and thus broaden the ECL spectrum of t-GQD-NAs. For the possible SP2 connecting route to produce large-sized GQDs from small-sized ones, the average size of GQDs in t-GQD-NAs should be larger than that of conventional free GQDs. This is why t-GQD-NAs may have longer emission wavelength compared with free GQDs. It should be noted here that t-GQD-NAs are not completely made of various-sized GQDs, but they may also contain some graphene nanoribbons. Hence t-GQD-NAs not only behave like GQDs in ECL emission, but also have some optical properties of graphene or SWCNTs. For examples, the dispersion solutions of t-GQD-NAs are brown to black (Fig. S1), which is similar to those of graphene and SWCNTs. The strong UV–Vis absorption activity of graphene ribbons on t-GQD-NAs may block light-excitation process of adjacent GQD centers and thus lead to the inhibition of photoluminescence (i.e. fluorescence) emission of t-GQD-NAs.
